              "width": 800,
              "height": 52,
              "rotate": 0,
              "content": "<p style='font-size:28px;font-weight:800;color:#f1f5f9;'>👛 What is a Crypto Wallet?</p>",
              "defaultFontName": "Inter",
              "defaultColor": "#f1f5f9"
            },
            {
              "id": "ew-s1-sub",
              "type": "text",
              "left": 24,
              "top": 66,
              "width": 800,
              "height": 30,
              "rotate": 0,
              "content": "<p style='font-size:13px;color:#64748b;font-weight:500;'>Your key to your crypto — not a physical wallet</p>",
              "defaultFontName": "Inter",
              "defaultColor": "#64748b"
            },
            {
              "id": "ew-s1-body",
              "type": "text",
              "left": 24,
              "top": 110,
              "width": 950,
              "height": 130,
              "rotate": 0,
              "content": "<p style='font-size:16px;color:#cbd5e1;line-height:1.8;'>A crypto wallet doesn't actually <em>store</em> your coins — your coins live on the blockchain. What a wallet stores are your <b style='color:#f87171;'>secret keys</b> — the passwords that prove the coins belong to you. Think of it like a <b style='color:#f1f5f9;'>mailbox key</b>. Your crypto is in the mailbox (blockchain). The key proves it's yours. Lose the key — someone else opens your mailbox.</p>",
              "defaultFontName": "Inter",
              "defaultColor": "#cbd5e1"
            },
            {
              "id": "ew-s1-box0",
              "type": "shape",
              "left": 24,
              "top": 270,
              "width": 220,
              "height": 120,
